  {
    "id": "10.1117/12.3094075",
    "title": "Optical-SDFNet: a hybrid optical-driven neural operator for aerodynamic pressure field prediction",
    "authors": "Zhenzhou Niu, Qiang Liu",
    "abstract": "With the expanding application of computational fluid dynamics (CFD) in complex engineering scenarios, improving simulation efficiency while maintaining prediction accuracy has become a key issue. To address the high computational overhead and low modeling efficiency of traditional methods for high Reynolds number flow fields and complex geometries, this paper proposes a hybrid neural operator model that integrates a Unified Network (UNet) backbone, a Signed Distance Function (SDF) encoder, and a Finite Volume Graph Neural Network (FVGN). This model enhances geometric perception through SDF, extracts local features using UNet, and models surface topology using FVGN, achieving efficient fusion of multi-scale physical features. Experimental results demonstrate that this method significantly outperforms traditional neural networks on multiple public datasets, achieving excellent performance in prediction accuracy, inference speed, and model robustness. The method particularly improves reconstruction capabilities in high-pressure gradient regions. Further ablation experiments and visualization analysis validate the effectiveness and synergy of each module. This method provides an efficient and scalable solution for rapid aerodynamic prediction of complex three-dimensional structures, demonstrating excellent engineering practicality and potential for widespread adoption. Furthermore, by incorporating optical sensing data from wind tunnel experiments, the model achieves higher fidelity and better alignment with real-world aerodynamic conditions.",
